05208nam a22007575i 9781400828883DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008288837 a10.1515/97814008288832doi  a(DE-B1597)446643  a(OCoLC)979592692  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHD6971 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a174/.42221 aAnteby, Michel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoral Gray Zones :bSide Productions, Identity, and Regulation in an Aeronautic Plant /cMichel Anteby.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b5 halftones. 4 line illus. 1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Table -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. The Persistence of Organizational Gray Zones -- tPart One. The Motivations and the Setting -- t1. Revisiting Social Systems In Organizations -- t2. The Side Production Of Homers In Factories -- t3. The Pierreville Plant: Setting and Status Divides -- tPart Two. The Findings -- t4 Retirement Homers: An Entry into the Community -- t5. Homers Gone Wrong: Delimiting the Gray Zone -- t6. Shades of Homer Meanings: Occupational Variations -- t7. The Rise and Fall of Craftsmanship -- t8. Trading in Identity Incentives -- tPart Three. The Implications -- t9. Organizational Gray Zones as Identity Distillers -- t10. Identities, Control, And Moralities -- tAppendix A. Data and Methods -- tAppendix B. Position In The Field -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnyone who has been employed by an organization knows not every official workplace regulation must be followed. When management consistently overlooks such breaches, spaces emerge in which both workers and supervisors engage in officially prohibited, yet tolerated practices--gray zones. When discovered, these transgressions often provoke disapproval; when company materials are diverted in the process, these breaches are quickly labeled theft. Yet, why do gray zones persist and why are they unlikely to disappear? In Moral Gray Zones, Michel Anteby shows how these spaces function as regulating mechanisms within workplaces, fashioning workers' identity and self-esteem while allowing management to maintain control. The book provides a unique window into gray zones through its in-depth look at the manufacture and exchange of illegal goods called homers, tolerated in a French aeronautic plant. Homers such as toys for kids, cutlery for the kitchen, or lamps for homes, are made on company time with company materials for a worker's own purpose and use. Anteby relies on observations at retirees' homes, archival data, interviews, and surveys to understand how plant workers and managers make sense of this tacit practice. He argues that when patrolled, gray zones like the production of homers offer workplaces balanced opportunities for supervision as well as expression. Cautioning against the hasty judgment that gray zone practices are simply wrong, Moral Gray Zones contributes to a deeper understanding of the culture, group dynamics, and deviance found in organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAircraft industryxCase studiesxFrancexFrance. 0aAircraft industryzFrancevCase studies. 0aGroup identity. 0aHomers (Manufactures). 0aIndustrial relationsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aOrganizational behaviorxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPsychology, Industrial. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9